</li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/topics/scriptures">"Scriptures"</a>. The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2007-12-25</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Scriptures&amp;rft.pub=The+Church+of+Jesus+Christ+of+Latter-day+Saints&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.churchofjesuschrist.org%2Ftopics%2Fscriptures&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+the+Church+of+Jesus+Christ+of+Latter-day+Saints" class="Z3988"></span>: "On September 22, 1827, an angel named Moroni—the last Book of Mormon prophet—delivered these records to the Prophet Joseph Smith."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The Church of Christ was organized in the log cabin of <a href="/wiki/Joseph_Smith,_Sr." class="mw-redirect" title="Joseph Smith, Sr.">Joseph Smith, Sr.</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Manchester_(town),_New_York" class="mw-redirect" title="Manchester (town), New York">Manchester</a> area, near <a href="/wiki/Rochester,_New_York" title="Rochester, New York">Rochester</a>, followed by a meeting the next Sunday in nearby <a href="/wiki/Fayette,_New_York" title="Fayette, New York">Fayette</a> at the house of <a href="/wiki/Peter_Whitmer,_Sr." class="mw-redirect" title="Peter Whitmer, Sr.">Peter Whitmer, Sr.</a> Nevertheless, one of Smith's histories and an 1887 reminiscence by <a href="/wiki/David_Whitmer" title="David Whitmer">David Whitmer</a> say the church was organized at the Whitmer house in Fayette. (Whitmer, however, had already told a reporter in 1875 that the church was organized in Manchester. <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFWhitmer1875" class="citation cs2">Whitmer, John C. (August 7, 1875), <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.sidneyrigdon.com/dbroadhu/IL/mischig.htm#080775">"The Golden Tables"</a>, <i>Chicago Times</i></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Chicago+Times&amp;rft.atitle=The+Golden+Tables&amp;rft.date=1875-08-07&amp;rft.aulast=Whitmer&amp;rft.aufirst=John+C.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.sidneyrigdon.com%2Fdbroadhu%2FIL%2Fmischig.htm%23080775&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+the+Church+of+Jesus+Christ+of+Latter-day+Saints" class="Z3988"></span>.) The LDS Church refers to Fayette as the place of organization in all its official <a href="/wiki/Publication" title="Publication">publications</a>.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFSmith1835" class="citation book cs1">Smith, Joseph (1835). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/57?lang=eng"><i>Doctrine and Covenants 57</i></a>. pp.&#160;57:1–3.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Doctrine+and+Covenants+57&amp;rft.pages=57%3A1-3&amp;rft.date=1835&amp;rft.aulast=Smith&amp;rft.aufirst=Joseph&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.churchofjesuschrist.org%2Fstudy%2Fscriptures%2Fdc-testament%2Fdc%2F57%3Flang%3Deng&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+the+Church+of+Jesus+Christ+of+Latter-day+Saints" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
